<TEXT>
the senate appropriations committee on thursday 
approved a 144 billion foreign aid bill that would slap 
restrictions on us aid to el salvador and give poland more aid 
than president bush has sought 
the panel also voted to reverse a fouryearold reagan 
administration policy that barred us aid to the united nations 
population fund and killed an effort to cut aid to greece 
the committee sent the measure to the full senate which is 
scrambling to complete work on the 13 appropriations bills needed to 
run the government before the new fiscal year begins on oct 1 
el salvadors 85 million in aid for the coming year would be 
divided into three slices to be sent at fourmonth intervals only if 
the new rightist government of president alfredo cristiani makes 
progress toward curbing death squad activity and making peace with 
leftist rebels fighting his government 
the final installment would be in effect subject to a veto by 
congressional committees with jurisdiction over foreign aid money 
sen patrick leahy dvt sponsor of the provision was able to 
prevail over the objections of the bush administration because he 
won the support of sen dennis deconcini dariz considered a 
swing vote on the issue but republicans were confident they had the 
votes to remove the restrictions when the measure comes to the 
senate floor as early as next week 
bush already has managed to eliminate restrictions on salvadoran 
aid from a house version of the foreign aid bill passed in july 
cristianis government is involved in peace talks in mexico with 
the leftist fmln rebels aimed at ending a decade of fighting that 
has cost more than 70000 lives death squads linked to cristianis 
arena party have been blamed for most of the deaths 
the committee also removed from the bill a provision that would 
have let the president cut aid to greece so long as military aid 
money previously sent remains unspent greekamerican groups had 
lobbied hard to eliminate the provision 
and it scaled back from 85 million to 45 million a fund to 
support private enterprise in poland even the scaledback amount 
was far more than the 10 million bush promised during his trip to 
eastern europe in july 
the election of a new noncommunistdominated government in 
poland has made that country an irresistible object of praise and 
reward for us lawmakers but the panel apparently backed down from 
the figure leahys subcommittee had adopted a day earlier in the 
face of budget realities 
sen barbara mikulski dmd prevailed 1512 on her amendment to 
earmark 15 million for the united nations population fund which 
manages population control programs worldwide 
the reagan administration had banned money to the organization in 
1985 contending that the agency was supporting forced abortions and 
sterilization in china mikulskis amendment would require the 
agency to keep us funds in a separate account which cannot be used 
for any programs in china 
as usual the largest recipients of us foreign aid in the 
measure are israel with 18 billion in military aid and 12 
billion in economic aid and egypt which gets 13 billion in 
military and 815 million in economic aid 
the bill also includes 160 million for the multilateral 
assistance initiative for the philippines together with authority 
for the president to send an additional 40 million to meet his full 
request for 200 million the house voted 160 million for the 
program 
</TEXT>
