<DOCNO> AP890914-0002 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
methane gas ignited and flashed like a 
flame thrower through a coal mine wednesday killing 10 miners in 
the nations worst coal mine disaster in five years 
there were conflicting reports of the number of injuries in the 
930 am fire at the william station mine in western kentucky but 
its parent company costain coal inc said no one had been trapped 
underground 
the mine run by costains subsidiary pyro mining co had been 
cited by the federal mine safety and health administration for high 
levels of methane gas about two months ago costain president 
charles schulties acknowledged at a news conference wednesday night 
it was the fourth fatal accident at the mine since it opened in 
february 1983 including a 1986 death that may have been related to 
methane according to state and federal safety records nearly a 
year ago three miners were hurt in a blasting accident 
methane the major ingredient of natural gas is found naturally 
in coal seams mine ventilation systems normally keep it below 
explosive concentrations 
early in the day the kentucky state police and the msha reported 
three miners had been burned in the fire a document the company 
submitted to state officials included the names of two miners who 
were listed as being injured 
schulties however told a news conference about six hours after 
the fire that there were no injuries and officials at area 
hospitals reported receiving no injured miners webster county 
deputy coroner paul tompkins also said late wednesday that no miners 
had been injured 
there was no immediate explanation for the discrepancy 
the death toll made it the nations worst coal mine disaster 
since 27 miners were killed in 1984 in a mine in utah said msha 
spokesman frank ogorman 
the ignition point of the fire apparently was near part of a 
mining machine that was being dismantled to be moved ogorman said 
the exact cause of the fire was not immediately known but msha 
spokesman sam stafford said such fires are usually caused when a 
piece of metal equipment hits stone and causes a spark 
stafford said such fires are small but like a flame thrower 
company officials said the miners who died were about 1000 feet 
underground when the explosion occurred jim greenlee an executive 
vice president of costain coal said 14 to 15 miners were in the 
immediate area when the jet of flame erupted and another 15 workers 
within 1000 feet 
there was smoke in the area and it took some time to locate all 
the individuals greenlee said 
rescue teams were sent into the shaft to remove the bodies said 
state trooper ed brady 
theres an indication that some of them had survived the 
initial explosion and succumbed to the smoke and dust schulties 
said well know more about that when the coroner issues his 
report 
ogorman said the dead were believed to have died of carbon 
monoxide poisoning 
officials believed some of the dead miners survived initially 
because some of them were found wearing selfrescuing units which 
provide a source of fresh air for miners in emergencies schulties 
said he did not provide additional details 
public protection secretary teddy colley identified the dead as 
lynn ashmore and kenneth reed of slaughters roger clifford and mark 
hedges of morganfield rick ferguson and curtis scott of 
madisonville terry harris and anthony mcelroy of providence warren 
stewart of mortons gap and and james tinsley of marion no ages were 
immediately available 
police sealed off the area around the mine and families of the 
dead miners were directed to a company headquarters building just 
outside wheatcroft a town of about 300 people 
all employees were immediately pulled out of the mine and all 
workers had been accounted for schulties said kathy snyder an 
msha official who attended the news conference said her agency and 
the kentucky department of mines and minerals would begin an 
investigation on thursday 
the mine which schulties said employs 367 miners on three 
shifts is about 140 miles southwest of louisville and 40 miles 
southwest of evansville ind 
in 1986 a foreman died in an explosion at the mine a federal 
investigation determined that methane or dust had been set off by 
the improper use of explosives during blasting excessive 
accumulations of loose coal and coal dust were also blamed 
last sept 22 a blasting accident ignited gas or coal dust 
burning three miners according to state mine department records 
state inspectors ordered the mine closed that day but allowed it to 
reopen the next day 
in 1984 a worker was run over by a vehicle at the mine in 
separate accidents in 1985 a worker was crushed against a wall 
while working on a machine and a mechanic was electrocuted 
mayor larry cowan who worked 23 years in mines said most people 
of the town earn their livings in the coal industry 
we know invariably it could happen but its always supposed 
to be someone else cowan said 
the mine was described as a highly mechanized longwall operation 
in longwall mining a mining machine continuously moves a cutter 
from side to side along a long exposed coal face 
as the cutter is moved forward with conveyors which remove the 
loosened coal hydraulic jacks are positioned to support the newly 
exposed mine roof behind the jacks the layers of rock that form 
the roof are allowed to collapse 
before longwall mining techniques and machines were developed 
pillars of coal had to be left in the mine to support the overlying 
rock layers 
</TEXT>
