<TEXT>
imelda marcos wants to begin an anticrime 
campaign directed at filipino youthgang members and police say its 
a good idea despite her being under indictment 
maj david benson head of the honolulu police departments 
juvenile division said the former philippine first lady has a 
knowledge of the philippine culture that we dont and her stature 
could really have an effect on some of these kids 
of the estimated 550 gang members on the island of oahu 45 
percent are filipino benson said wednesday many are involved in 
drugrelated and violent crimes 
mrs marcos said she wanted to meet with gang members mostly 
teenage boys individually or in groups and listen to their 
problems 
i dont have to be their role model but everybody would like a 
friend everybody needs love she said 
mrs marcos acknowledged critics might call her an unsuitable 
counselor because she and her husband former philippine president 
ferdinand marcos face us racketeering charges accusing them of 
stealing nearly 200 million from their homeland and stashing it in 
the united states 
she said she would draw on her experience as mayor of manila and 
that she wanted to repay the filipino community in hawaii for its 
support since marcos was exiled to hawaii after being ousted in 
february 1986 
benson said no program had been worked out but he would work 
with filipino community groups and mrs marcos to design a 
counseling program 
mrs marcos is free on 5 million bail and is to stand trial 
march 14 in new york her husband has been separated from the case 
because of ill health 
the 72yearold marcos remained in critical condition at st 
francis medical center suffering from multiple organ failure 
