<TEXT>
city opera officials canceled wednesdays season 
opener of the barber of seville after the musicians announced 
they will picket in full dress in a wage dispute with the company 
we will not perform while they are on strike said martin 
oppenheimer the companys attorney and board vice chairman future 
performances will be canceled until the strike is resolved he said 
the sad part about this is we will never have the 
performances that have to be canceled because of the strike he 
said 
judy west a spokeswoman for local 802 of the associated 
musicians of greater new york said a strike is always 
difficult especially on the musicians and is not welcomed by the 
union 
the 69 musicians voted in favor of the strike tuesday night after 
extensive negotiations west said the union served the company with 
a sevenday strike notice last week 
theyve gotten nowhere in climbing over two stumbling blocks 
west said 
the union wants wage parity with the lyric opera in chicago 
union officials say city opera musicians get 755 for 19 hours of 
work and chicago musicians get 1048 for a 21hour work week 
the union also wants guaranteed work weeks restored to the 
contract under the old contract the union says the orchestra was 
guaranteed 23 full weeks of work plus six weeks of added employment 
called supplemental employment benefits 
the company is offering only the 23 weeks of work 
oppenheimer said the lyric opera charges twice what city opera 
does and is the only game in town 
we have our own economics here in new york where costs are 
higher and competition more intense he said 
no negotiations were scheduled oppenheimer said 
</TEXT>
