a transformation in the nature of the soviet system and for a 
qualitative improvement in eastwest relations 
but eagleburger told an audience at georgetown university that 
gorbachev was driven by severe economic problems threatening to make 
the soviet union incapable of competing with the western democracies 
we are hearing we need to take measures to ensure the success 
of gorbachevs reforms eagleburger said this however is not 
the task of american foreign policy nor should it be that of our 
western partners 
he continued our task after all is to devise policies which 
will serve our interests whether mr gorbachev succeeds or fails 
in the audience was soviet ambassador yuri dubinin next week 
secretary of state james a baker iii will meet in jackson hole 
wyo with soviet foreign minister eduard a shevardnadze to make 
preparations for a superpower summit 
gorbachev is no anticommunist eagleburger said and he 
intends to make the soviet union as strong as he possibly can 
the us official also warned against extending trade and arms 
control concessions to moscow without the kind of systematic 
reforms which alone can make for a stable and confident relationship 
between east and west 
delivering a lecture to memorialize the late american diplomat 
samuel berger the deputy secretary of state also 
sketched a gloomy picture of cambodias future he said the 
united states does not have it within its power to determine the 
future government and that all rival factions must be represented 
this would appear to include the khmer rouge which was accused of 
murdering some 1 million cambodians while ruling the south asian 
country a peace conference in paris collapsed in late august 
predicted optimistically that the new government in south 
africa may begin dismantling the system of racial segregation known 
as apartheid the chances for change over the next few months are 
substantial eagleburger said 
in the speech eagleburger concentrated on the future of the 
western alliance and its stance toward the soviet union under 
gorbachev 
he has made hopeful pronouncements on arms reductions and has 
slowed the overseas adventurism which did so much to galvanize 
western solidarity in the early 1980s eagleburger said 
and yet the us official said herein lies a danger to 
western interests that with the perception growing among the 
western public that the soviet threat has diminished there will be a 
tendency among the member states of the nato alliance to compete in 
expanding their relationships with the east 
already eagleburger said without offering any specifics some 
western nations are showing tendencies toward unilateralism in 
trade matters 
he added obviously it is in the europeans interest as much 
if not more than our own to avoid bankrolling merely cosmetic 
soviet reforms or reach arms control agreements which undermine 
natos ability to deter aggression 
