<TEXT>
richard c breeden president bushs nominee to 
head the securities and exchange commission said today that 
vigorous securities law enforcement was good for market integrity 
and could help us markets compete globally for foreign investment 
breeden also told the senate banking committee at his 
confirmation hearing that criminal sanctions are a helpful adjunct 
to a civil enforcement program 
breedens testimony followed opening remarks by committee 
chairman sen donald w riegle jr dmich that the next sec chief 
must be the strongest chairman to date in enforcement of 
securities law 
the senator contended that current securities laws have an 
inadequate ability to deter serious and flagrant violators 
when asked by sen christopher dodd dconn how he squared his 
reputation as a freemarket advocate with the need for strong 
enforcement breeden said it was a perfectly legitimate role for 
government to keep the markets clean 
breeden also said that while decadesold securities laws do not 
address the current global competition against domestic markets i 
think that can be attractive to foreign investors if us markets 
are considered free of corruption 
breeden was the white house point man on the savings and loan 
bailout he did not speak with reporters about his views on the 
issues facing the securities industry after his nomination was 
announced aug 14 instead issuing a statement that he would speak 
only to the committee considering his nomination 
reigle has suggested that breeden lacks the background to handle 
issues such as leveraged buyouts insider trading that face the sec 
mr breeden is highly intelligent and did fine work on the sampl 
reform package and in other governmental assignments riegle said 
earlier in a statement after breedens nomination yet he brings a 
limited direct market experience to this critical assignment and 
that is a matter of some concern when the sec faces a time of epic 
challenge 
among the issues before the sec that breeden was expected to 
address were leveraged buyouts insider trading and the programmed 
trading that has led to uncontrolled stock market fluctuations 
breeden was also expected to answer questions about whether the 
sec should have a say in overseas takeover battles such as the 
ongoing fight for the british bat industries plc that involve us 
jobs and shareholders 
the sec is also going through internal upheaval as it faces 
pressing financial market issues 
in addition to ruder two of the other four commissioners have 
indicated they are leaving theres also a vacancy in the post of 
enforcement division head 
a banking attorney before he joined the white house staff 
breeden helped write the bush plan for bailing out the sampl industry 
and then shepherded the bill through congress 
he also worked for thenvice president bush in the reagan 
administration 
