<TEXT>
oaklands school district has been plagued 
by charges of corruption and thievery and faces a fiscal crisis that 
could force it to accept a 10 million bailout and a stateappointed 
overseer 
the california assembly on thursday approved the bailout measure 
and sent it to the governor for signing if approved oakland would 
become the states first district taken over by the state without 
the school boards approval 
in the past six months police have arrested eight school 
employees on charges ranging from grand theft to forgery the entire 
sevenmember school board has been subpoenaed by a county grand 
jury and a threemonth newspaper investigation uncovered a 
mafiastyle patronage system allegedly run by top officials known as 
the family 
in addition the district has been unable to hire a 
superintendent to take over stewardship of californias 
fifthlargest school district since the previous chief administrator 
left in december 
angry residents responding to the turmoil have launched a 
recall drive to oust school board members 
the district with a 14 million deficit in the current 228 
million budget is teetering on the verge of bankruptcy the school 
board on wednesday approved a financing plan that uses school 
property as collateral but state schools chief bill honig and 
alameda county schools superintendent william berck oppose the 
arrangement as fiscally unstable 
honig called the budget plan hokey and said district 
mismanagement has created problems that are now bursting out all 
over 
nobodys running the show he said they have no longterm 
plan to get out of the problems they need fiscal policies they 
need personnel policies and they need management policies 
state assemblyman elihu harris sponsored the legislation to 
provide a 10 million loan and put in place a state monitor to 
oversee the districts financial operations and make sure they 
develop and adhere to a longterm plan 
these are not problems that just surfaced in oakland harris 
said thursday some have been around for 15 or 16 years if the 
problems were new id suggest they could be solved internally but 
theyre not new 
more than 50000 residents signed a petition in support of 
harris proposed law now awaiting gov george deukmejians 
signature 
as the crisis grows police estimate as many as 50 district 
employees may be arrested before their investigation is completed 
worried parents are enrolling their children in private schools in 
record numbers 
critics blame top leaders for the crisis in the 50000student 
district they say a looseknit system of close friends working to 
protect each others jobs has eroded authority and cleared the way 
for illegal activity 
several school officials many of whom will speak only on the 
condition of anonymity say senior school board member darlene 
lawson is at the center of the alleged patronage system 
lawson who did not return telephone calls seeking comment 
thursday has denied that she heads the family and has accused 
critics of launching a racist drive to purge the district of many 
black administrators 
the firstever grand jury probe of the schools began in 1984 one 
year after a black majority was elected to the board for the first 
time lawson wrote in the tribune of oakland following the 
newspapers twoday report 
lawson who is black said educational problems have been ignored 
as politicians pursue an elitist and undemocratic political 
agenda 
honig described the districts crisis as just a sick 
situation and rejected the charge of racism 
the last refuge of scoundrels is the false claim of 
racism he said nobody wants to take over oakland weve got 
enough to do they should do their jobs eventually the people 
there who are claiming a plot are going to have to realize that they 
are the problem 
