<TEXT>
the federal reserve board has given approval 
for banks to double the amount of revenue that their securities 
subsidiaries can earn from certain underwriting operations 
the change announced wednesday will mean that a banks 
securities subsidary will be able to earn up to 10 percent of its 
revenues from the underwriting activities up from the previous 
limit of 5 percent 
the activities covered include underwriting of corporate debt 
municipal revenue bonds commercial paper mortgagebacked 
securities and securities backed by consumer loans 
the rest of the revenue must come from other types of businesses 
such as the underwriting of general obligation bonds issued by 
municipalities and us government securities two less risky areas 
of underwriting that have always been opened to banks 
the feds decision which came on a 60 vote drew praise from 
the banking industry which has been pressing to be allowed to 
expand further into the securities area 
these decisions correctly open the securities door a bit wider 
for banking and remind everyone of the need to get oldfashioned 
bank regulations in sync with the modern marketplace said thomas 
p rideout president of the american bankers association and a vice 
chairman of first union national bank of charlotte nc the 
benefits of prudent bank entry into securities far outweigh 
potential concerns alleged by our protectionist competitors 
rideout said that the bankers group hoped that the fed would 
expand the income level to 25 percent in the future 
the fed first approved bank underwriting activities for bank 
subsidiaries in 1987 and added corporate debt to the list of 
acceptable securities in january of this year the board has 
indicated that it would decide in a year whether to allow banks to 
underwrite stock 
the feds decision wednesday fits in with a trend in recent years 
in which advances in bank deregulation have come through 
administrative and court decisions because of a political deadlock 
in congress over the question of restructuring the financial system 
the bush administration is currently studying the question of 
what changes it will recommend making in the depressionera 
glasssteagall act the law which separated commerical and 
investment banking as part of the reforms passed by congress 
following the 1929 stock market crash 
