<TEXT>
britain continues to lead the world as a center 
for currency trading but the united states and japan are catching 
up as trading volume continues to mushroom central bank surveys 
show 
daily trading in currencies totaled 187 billion in london 
1289 billion in new york and 1152 billion in tokyo according to 
april surveys released by the central banks wednesday 
currency trading worldwide has more than doubled since 1986 the 
last time surveys were done figures for different countries cannot 
simply be added up because crossborder trades are counted twice in 
the buyers country and the sellers 
the growth in currency trading far exceeds the expansion of 
international trade in goods and services which is the underlying 
reason for currency trading 
although businesses need to trade currencies to do business 
abroad the vast majority of currency trading today is speculation 
by banks and other dealers statistics indicate 
big banks devote large staffs to playing the market buying and 
selling currencies by the minute in hopes of pocketing profits by 
guessing shortterm price trends 
in the united states only about 12 percent of banks dealings 
are with industrial companies and other institutions that need 
currencies for purposes other than speculation according to 
gretchen greene a senior vice president at the federal reserve bank 
of new york 
the rapid growth in currency trading reflects the closer 
connections among stock and bond markets around the world and the 
attractiveness of dealing in currencies for speculation and hedging 
among other factors greene said 
in london average daily currency trading rose 107 percent to 
187 billion from 90 billion in 1986 
in new york trading rose 120 percent to 1289 billion a day 
from 585 billion three years earlier 
the tokyo market showed the fastest growth up 140 percent to 
1152 billion from 48 billion 
in comparison world exports rose by about a third from 1986 to 
1988 according to united nations figures estimates for 1989 are 
not yet available 
after the big three trading centers came switzerland 57 
billion hong kong 49 billion france 26 billion the 
netherlands 16 billion and canada 15 billion up 57 percent 
canada was the only one of the smaller markets surveyed in 1986 
more than 300 billion worth of dollars marks yen pounds 
francs and other currencies change hands daily surveys by the banks 
reveal 
the total is probably more than 400 billion a day although 
estimates are difficult because of the doublecounting problem 
central bankers plan to share information in order to eliminate 
doublecounting of crossborder trades and come up with a net figure 
for worldwide currency trading possibly later this year or early in 
1990 greene said 
the central banks surveyed banks other financial institutions 
and brokers over 20 business days in april the federal reserve has 
surveyed currency trading every three years since 1977 and was 
joined in 1986 by a few other central banks 
the volume of trading is so huge that it often overwhelms efforts 
by central banks to stabilize currency rates such as by selling 
dollars on the open market when the dollar is getting too high 
for example federal reserve dollar sales of 130 million in the 
us market would equal only onetenth of 1 percent of total trading 
on an average day the new statistics show 
but greene said central banks still can be effective because 
although total trading volume is huge the imbalances between supply 
and demand that cause prices to move are much narrower in other 
words supplying a small sum of dollars to the market could soak up 
the excess demand and halt a price rise 
the greatest concentration of trading continued to be in the 
dollar against the west german mark japanese yen and british pound 
the surveys showed 
trades that didnt involve the dollar such as selling marks for 
yen grew in importance they rose to 11 percent of total volume 
from 4 percent in london they totaled about 4 percent in new york 
no new york comparison for 1986 was available 
