<TEXT>
texas air corp is paying 45 million worth of 
eastern airlines pension fund obligations due friday to help the 
strikebound carrier save some cash 
the payment by the parent company will be in the form of a loan 
that eastern lawyers said would be repayed during the airlines 
bankruptcy reorganization 
us bankruptcy judge burton r lifland approved a proposal 
wednesday for payment of 983 million to easterns seven employee 
pension plans including those of striking workers and salaried 
employees 
eastern will pay just 27 million of the total and payment of the 
remaining 263 million will be deferred until next july 1 
it certainly is in everybodys best interest that the funding 
of those plans is completely sourced lifland said 
the plan was reached after discussions among eastern its 
creditors committee and the internal revenue service which is 
responsible for overseeing payments to pension funds 
lawyers for eastern said the plan gives eastern a break by 
deferring some payment until later in the course of its chapter 11 
proceedings and transferring other payments to texas air 
it saves eastern a lot of cash during the chapter 11 case 
eastern lawyer bruce zirinsky said 
the 45 million to be paid by texas air will be held as a claim 
on the eastern estate that will be resolved as part of easterns 
reorganization 
the agreement was opposed by lawyers for the air line pilots 
association and easterns preferred shareholders committee lawyers 
for the shareholders said any cash outlay would hurt the airline 
while the pilots lawyers wanted full payment into the funds 
of the total amount due 784 million represents money owed for 
pension plans ending last year and 199 million is for money due 
under waivers granted by the irs for previous plan years zirinsky 
said 
eastern has been under chapter 11 bankruptcy protection from 
creditors since march 9 five days after its machinists pilots and 
flight attendants walked off the job 
the airline has been selling aircraft routes and airport gates 
to raise money to pay off its 23 billion debt it gradually has 
rebuilt as a smaller carrier under a reorganization plan filed in 
july 
eastern officials recently disclosed to creditors that the 
airline will have about 370 million less in cash by year end than 
first projected having abandoned a plan to sell its latin american 
routes 
